'''Kwamena Bartels''' (born 27 October 1947)<ref name="Bio">{{cite web |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/people/person.php?ID=221 |title=Kwamina Bartels Profile |author= |date= |work= |publisher=GhanaWeb |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref> is a [[Ghana]]ian [[politician]] and former government minister of the [[New Patriotic Party]].

==Biography==
After graduating from secondary school in 1968, Bartels was admitted to the [[University of Ghana]], where he studied law. After obtaining his bachelor's degree in 1971, Bartels continued his studies at the [[Ghana School of Law]] in order to become a professional lawyer.<ref name="Bio" />

In 1979, Bartels first contested for a seat in the [[Parliament of Ghana]], but was defeated by a [[People's National Party (Ghana)|People's National Party]] candidate. In 1992, Bartels again stood for election in [[Agona West (Ghana parliament constituency)|Agona West]] constituency, but withdrew after his party boycotted the 1992 election due to alleged [[electoral fraud]]. In 1996, Bartels was elected MP for the [[Ablekuma North (Ghana parliament constituency)|Ablekuma North]] constituency.<ref name="Bio" /> He subsequently became Minister in charge of Private Sector and PSI (2005-2006), Minister of Information & National Orientation (2006-2007), and Minister of the Interior (2007-2008).<ref name="AvDevInfo">{{cite web |url=http://www.afdevinfo.com/htmlreports/peo/peo_1497.html |title=People Record: Kwamena Bartels |author= |date= |work= |publisher=AfDevInfo |accessdate=13 April 2012}}</ref>

Bartels was fired from the cabinet by President [[John Kufuor]] in 2008, allegedly due to his involvement in the stealing of forty-two parcels of [[cocaine]] which were confiscated by the police.<ref>{{cite news |title=Enquirer: Why Bartels Was Fired |author= |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=144387 |newspaper=GhanaWeb |date= |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref> It is also alleged that Bartels channeled considerable amounts of a US-sponsored government fund meant for the Ghanaian private sector to companies owned by his daughters and sons-in-law.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kwamena Bartels' Turn Soon |author= |url=http://www.ghanaweb.com/GhanaHomePage/NewsArchive/artikel.php?ID=167198 |newspaper=GhanaWeb |date= |accessdate=9 April 2012}}</ref>

==Family==
Bartels is a member of the Afro-European [[Bartels#Ghanaian family|Bartels family]], whose ancestor [[Cornelius Ludewich Bartels]] was Governor-General of the [[Dutch Gold Coast]] between 1798 and 1804, and whose son [[Carel Hendrik Bartels]] was the most important mulatto trader on the Gold Coast in the second quarter of the nineteenth century.<ref name="GCDB">{{cite web |url=http://gcdb.doortmontweb.org/getperson.php?personID=I277&tree=Africa |title=Bartels, Carel Hendrik |author= |date=2012-04-06 |work= |publisher=GoldCoastDataBase |accessdate=19 April 2012}}</ref>

