== About Me ==

Ecthelion is a [[handle]] I have used, and I got it from the [[Lord of the Rings]] trilogy.

I was born in [[South Korea]] but I grew up in the [[United States]].

Um, what the hell else can I put in here before it turns into a [[Facebook]] or [[MySpace]] profile?
Let's see: I am a recent graduate of [[Northwestern University]], earned my [[B.S.]] in [[biomedical engineering]] there, but I probably should have been a political science/history/English triple major instead (as I seem to have more enthusiasm for topics in those fields and probably would have more aptitude in classes thereof, not that I don't have any in engineering - I do). I have completed my MPH (that's master of [[public health]]) at the [[University of Medicine and Dentistry of New Jersey]] (I'm not from Jersey; long story involved as to how I got here), and served as the president of the student government there for one school year. After a one-semester stint at [[St. George's University]] School of Medicine, I had to return home for a variety of reasons, and am currently pursuing my doctorate in the Ph.D. program in epidemiology at [[Michigan State University]]. I do intend to return to medical school upon the completion of my doctorate, be it St. George's or another accredited institution (St. George's does not allow for leaves of absence of longer than a semester, and I would have to re-start at the very beginning if I were to return).

I play the [[piano]] and [[violin]], I [[ski]], I play [[tennis]], I sometimes play golf (but I suck at that), I'm a black belt in [[taekwondo]], and I practice [[kendo]] as well. I used to run regularly, but since I started getting [[shin splints]], I have taken up [[swimming]] (I used to be on my high school swimming team) instead. I do cook sometimes (but it's such a pain in the ass). While I am pretty well-read, I still have a voracious appetite for books, especially ones that require lots of thinking during and after the reading.

This piece of trivia may be useless to some, but useful for others: I used to be on the chess team in junior high school, and at my peak performance then, I defeated my coach in an after-school match. It only happened once though, and it occurred by some slick diversionary conversation on my part, not through any feat of skill (and my coach was gracious enough to just let me have the win).

I used to be a [[United States Marine]] reservist while an undergrad at Northwestern, but because of conflicts between the reserves and school, I requested and received a general discharge.

I am [[Roman Catholic]].

I like [[Korean food]], but I am not averse to other foods, ethnic or otherwise. I especially like [[Chipotlé]] (it is my most favorite restaurant, franchised or not; and I am well-aware that it doesn't exactly qualify as "ethnic" food ''per se'').

My father is descended from the [[Korean]] [[Lee_(Korean_name) | Lees]] of [[Gyeongju]] (경주 이 씨), and my mother is descended from the Korean [[Kim_(Korean_name) | Kims]] of [[Gimhae]] (김해 김 씨). According to my [[jokbo]] (족보) or family genealogic record, I am of the 41st generation of my branch (익제공 파) of the Gyeongju Lees.

Currently, I teach the [[MCAT]], [[PCAT]], [[GRE]], and [[GMAT]] for [[Kaplan, Inc. | Kaplan]], which I like to call the "evil empire of the test prep industry." All joking aside, it's a pretty good job for a student; anyone who can score at or above the 90th percentile on a standardized exam (that's Kaplan's cutoff; I scored in the 93rd percentile, a 34R, on my MCAT, and on the 99th percentile, a 450, on the PCAT - my GRE score breaks down as 790 quantitative, 690 verbal, and 6.0 writing, while the 730 on GMAT was a simulated score) has a pretty good shot at getting a teaching job with Kaplan. I also recently qualified on examinations to join the high-IQ society [[Mensa International|Mensa]].

I'm a stickler for historical accuracy and correctness, but I don't care for political correctness because I feel that it skirts around the issues and doesn't face the real problems head-on. As a rather proud Korean, I might be partial to the Korean take on a lot of issues, but I am actually pretty fair and I know when the Korean take on something is inaccurate (which happens more often than you'd think, even if the inaccuracy is not due to bias).

Oh, for miscellaneous information, my favorite sports teams are as follows: the [[Chicago White Sox]], the [[Chicago Bears]]...and that about sums it up.

I think I'm done with this.

